<HEADLINE> Villeneuve Wins Budapest F1 GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Canadian driver Jacques
Villeneuve cut double world champion Michael Schumacher's world
championship lead to three points Sunday when he beat Briton Damon
Hill on the last lap of the Hungarian Formula One Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve, behind the wheels of Williams, overtook defending
champion Hill at the last lap to snatch the fifth victory this
year and the ninth of his career.
</P>
<P>
Hill's Arrows car had developed throttle problems on the
penultimate lap but he hung on for second place, with Briton
Johnny Herbert in a Sauber third.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve has collected 53 points in the world title race,
only three points away from leader Schumacher, who finished fourth
here for Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher's younger brother Ralf came fifth in a Jordan ahead
of Japanese Shinji Nakano in a Prost.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve's teammate Heinz-Harald Frentzen of Germany, who had
briefly led the race, called it quits after 29 laps because of
engine problems. Both McLaren drivers Briton's David Coulthard
and Finn Mika Hakkinen also retired.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
