<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Gives Zambia Fund for Health Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has earmarked 57.75 million U.S. Dollars for
Zambia's health areas, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to UNICEF and the Government Program of Cooperation
for Women and Children report, the money will be used in primary
health care and nutrition education, planning and action for
women and children and country program support.
</P>
<P>
The overall goal of the program of cooperation is to
strengthen Zambia's capacities to promote sustained improvements
in the survival, development and welfare of women and children.
</P>
<P>
The program will help Zambia halt its increasing infant
mortality and stabilize the under-five mortality rate below 200
per 1,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
It will also help the country halt its increasing HIV
infection rate and increase access to clean water and sanitary
means of excreta disposal for 50 percent of rural and 100 percent
of urban households. 
</P>
</TEXT>
