<BODY>
<HEADLINE> KAL Crash Survivors Suffer From Psychological Disorders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Some of the survivors of the
crashed Korean Air Flight 801 in Guam, who have returned here for
medical treatment, suffer from severe psychological disorders
which could persist for an indefinite period, doctors said today.
</P>
<P>
"About 70 percent of the survivors face a wide spectrum of
symptoms such as psychological unrest, mood swings, memory loss
and other problems," said Kim Kwang-il, a doctor at Hanyang
University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Kim said that some patients suffer from despair, frustration and
deep remorse for a long period which could result in nervous
breakdowns, melancholia and even suicide.
</P>
<P>
Only 27 people survived after the Boeing 747 carrying 254
passengers and crew members crashed into a rocky hill near Guam's
Agana International Airport on August 6.
</P>
<P>
KAL survivors have been stricken with sorrow and the burden
when they found their relatives, friends or family members were
killed in the crash, said doctors.
</P>
<P>
Lee Chae-nam, 43, who lost her son, daughter and husband in the
crash, refused to meet with her relatives. He was transferred to the
Samsung Medical Center in southern Seoul Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Covering her face with a handkerchief, Lee cried, "I don't want
to meet my relatives. Leave me alone."
</P>
<P>
Lee Chang-woo, 29, said he couldn't close his eyes because of
the terrible image of darkness and the downed plane. He lost three
friends in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Son Sun-nyo, 23, who suffers from severe burns, is troubled by
horrible memories and nightmares.
</P>
<P>
Hong Hyon-sung, 36, who escaped with slight injuries, said, "I
can't get to sleep because I still hear children under the debris
shouting desperately 'Help me! Help me!'"
</P>
<P>
"Survivors of deadly accidents are apt to be afraid that
another big disaster will strike again and take their lives," said
Ha Kyu-sob, a psychiatrist at Seoul National University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
He added that the persistent stress may make them act
unreasonably and imprudently in their life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
