<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Most Cultivable Land Uncropped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 84 percent of Zambia's
cultivable land remains uncropped, according to a report edited
by the government and the United Nations agencies in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The immediate resource challenge is to make use of the
cultivable land and labor, said the report available here today.
</P>
<P>
The main resources that can support Zambia's future economic
development are its cultivable land, the abundance of labor and
the associated potential for developing the people's stock of
human capital, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Zambia has done little to develop its economic
potential due to misguided past policies, added the report.
</P>
<P>
The available natural resource based opportunities for the
development of agriculture were obscured by unfavorable policies
and by the general failure to make necessary investments in rural
infrastructure and services, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
