<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Departs for Direct Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides left here today for Switzerland to attend the second
round of the United Nations-sponsored direct talks between leaders
of the two communities in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press before his departure, Clerides said he
has got support of all Cypriot political parties for the second
round of talks on certain issues.
</P>
<P>
"First, to go to the talks, second, to submit our remarks on
the second U.N. document and third, to go there with good will to
discuss the fundamental aspects of the Cyprus problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
He avoided replying to questions concerning the strategy of the
Greek Cypriot side during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The second round of face-to-face talks between President
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will begin
Monday at the Hotel Righi Vaudois in Glion-sur-Montreux.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. announcement, a photo opportunity for a
pool of media representatives will be organized at the hotel at
the start of the talks and from then on, there will be no other
media access at the site of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
A press briefing will be held at the end of the talks on August
16, by U.N. Secretary-General's Special Advisor on the Cyprus
problem Diego Cordovez at the Palais des Nations. Cordovez will
preside over the five-day talks.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the talks is for the two communities to create
new constitutional and institutional structures which will allow
the people of both Cypriot communities to live together in peace,
the U.N. announcement said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash held their first round of talks, under
the U.N. auspices, at Troutbeck, near New York, from July 9-12.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides is accompanied by Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides, Government Spokesman Manolis Christofides, and his two
advisers, Attorney-General Alecos Markides and Under Secretary to
the president Pantelis Kouros.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite this island
nation as bi-communal, bi-zonal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
