<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Accuses U.S. Human Rights Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen today accused the United States of imposing its
so-called democracy and human rights on Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with "the Washington Times" and "the Washington
Post," Hun Sen said that the United States should learn a lesson
from the history, introspecting what it had done to the Cambodian
people.
</P>
<P>
He said the fire of the decades-long Cambodia War had been
ignited by the United States, which had cost tens of thousands of
Cambodians' lives.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is meaningless for Washington to have the
Cambodian people accept its so-called democracy and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said it is impossible that large-scale war would occur
again in today's Cambodia, which is facing the challenge of
achieving stable politics, economic development and elimination of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
he said that his government would abide by the Paris peace
accord as well as the result of the 1993 election so as to ensure
the free and just general elections scheduled for May 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
