<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Continues to Use Jordan's Aqaba Port as Key Supply Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today reassured Jordan of the
continuous using of the latter's Red Sea port of Aqaba as a key
route for receiving humanitarian aid despite of the planned
opening of a supply line through Syria.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Iraqi Minister of Industry and Mineral Resources Adnan
Alani made the promise here at a meeting with Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali and Minister of Trade, Industry and
Supply Hani Mulki.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time for an Iraqi cabinet minister to
make such assurance. Iraqi Minister of Commerce Mohammed
Mehdi Saleh had made the same assurance on August 3.
</P>
<P>
Alani, who arrived here Saturday, also called on Jordanian
authorities to increase exports to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This was part of the Iraqi effort to develop bilateral
relations with Jordan and strive for closer cooperation in
economic and trade sectors, he said
</P>
<P>
Mulki said on the occasion that Iraq would double its imports
via Aqaba more than that witnessed in the first phase of the
oil-for-food reached between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The deal allows Iraq to export oil worth two billion
U.S. dollars in a 6-month period to buy back food and medicine
badly needed in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the deal started last December and has been
renewed for another six months.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's promise to use Aqaba port came after Baghdad applied to
the U.N. for the opening of the Iraq-Syria border. This route, if
approved by the U.N., will facilitate the flow-in of the
Syrian-made goods which are cheaper than the Jordanian-made
products and provide European exporters a shorter transportation
line to Iraq than the one through Aqaba port.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's applyment has triggered fear among the Jordanian
businessmen of losing business with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Via Aqaba port, Iraq imported civilian goods and military
equipment during the Iraqi-Iranian war in the 1980s and Jordan
made more than one billion dollars every year from entrepot trade
through Aqaba port bound for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the Aqaba port lost its glory when the U.N. sanctions
was imposed on Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. Iraq has
since then relied more on its border with Turkey as well as its
own Um Qasr port, both of which were approved by the U.N. under
the oil-for-food deal for Baghdad to import humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been Iraq's largest trade partner for years, with
its exports of goods and services to Iraq totaled 220 million
dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0014 </DOCNO>
