<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Government Open for Dialogue with Political Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Salam Majali said here today that his government was, is and will
be open for holding talks with all political forces in the country
on issues of the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The one-person, one-vote system, which was one of the main
reasons for some political parties to boycott the elections,
conforms to the idea of equation among the Jordanian citizens and
the country's constitution, Radio Jordan quoted the prime minister
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Majali also called for reviewing the arrangements and measures
in connection with the forthcoming elections, which were earlier
dated as on November 4.
</P>
<P>
The arrangements for the elections must guarantee a fair, free
and democratic atmosphere for voting, he added.
</P>
<P>
Altogether six opposition parties decided to boycott the
elections because they opposed the Press and Publication Law, the
one-person, one-vote election system, the normalization of ties
with Israel and the government's measures to marginalize political
parties.
</P>
<P>
After the declaration of boycott, the government showed its
willingness to hold dialogues with the opposition parties in an
effort to settle the disputes.
</P>
<P>
But all the parties refused to cooperate with the government
and continue to keep their stance of boycott.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties now occupy 23 seats in the 80-member
Lower House of Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
