<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Aims Mission at Middle East Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross said here today that his current mission will focus on
restoring Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation following a
bloody suicide attack.
</P>
<P>
Ross told reporters after meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu earlier this morning that
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeline
Albright asked him to focus his efforts on security questions.
</P>
<P>
The security relationship between Israel and Palestine
should be established "in a way that is productive and effective,"
said Ross, adding that Albright will visit the region only after
progress is made on security.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here Saturday night to try to ease tensions
plunged deeper into crisis by a July 30 suicide bombing at an
Israeli market that killed 15 people, including two Islamic
suicide bombers, and wounded 170 others.
</P>
<P>
The militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) claimed
responsibility for the attack, which extinguished a glimpse of
optimism for resuming the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks that
have been stalled since Israel began building the Har Homa
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who left the prime minister's office for a meeting with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in the West Bank, said Clinton
and Albright also recognized there was "a political dimension that
has to be addressed".
</P>
<P>
Ross's comments seemed to please Israel, which has placed its
security needs above progress in peace talks, but will anger the
Palestinians who hoped Ross to address their concerns, especially
the punitive measures taken by Israel following the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Israel closed off the West Bank and Gaza after the market
attack, expelled Palestinians working in Israel and halted the
transfer of tax revenues it collected on Palestinian National
Authority's (PNA) behalf, and conditioned any resumption of talks
on Arafat cracking down on Islamic militant groups.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview with Reuters and CNN on Saturday,
Arafat said he was making a "100 percent effort" to arrest
militants trying to wreck peace moves.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Arafat made it clear that it was
unacceptable for Ross to focus his efforts only on Israel's
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also said on Saturday that he would raise with Ross the
issue of Israel's Jewish settlement policy on land occupied since
the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat refused to comment on
Ross's statements, saying the Palestinians were waiting to be
briefed by the envoy himself on the purpose of his trip. 
</P>
