<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Government Attacked As Hospital Queues Lengthen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Waiting lists in National Health
Service (NHS) hospitals are set to rise sharply over the next
year, despite Labor's election promise of swifter patient
treatment.
</P>
<P>
It could drive hospital waiting lists up by as much as 360,000
over the next two years, according to calculations based on the
Government's budget forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Chantrey Vellacott, a firm of accountants, said waiting lists
are set to rise by as many as 500 patients a day until the middle
of 1999 unless spending is increased.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Alan Milburn has admitted that waiting
lists will get longer in 44 of the 100 health authorities in
England and shorter in only four.
</P>
<P>
Among them, almost half the health authorities in England have
discreetly altered their contractual arrangements to allow for
longer waiting times.
</P>
<P>
South Essex, West Herts and West Sussex have told hospitals to
keep within maximum waiting times of 18 months in 1997-98,
compared with a maximum of 12 months last year.
</P>
<P>
The Chantrey Vellacott report warned of other unaccounted
costs, including three billion pounds (4.8 billion U.S. dollars) of
negligence claims and the cost of changing the date in computers
at the millennium.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Democrats said that before election, hardly a day
went by without Labor highlighting the problem of growing waiting
lists. One of the Government's key manifesto pledges was to take
100,000 people off waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
However, Simon Hughes, Liberal Democrat health spokesman,
said: "The harsh reality is that under Labor, waiting lists are
set to get longer."  
</P>
</TEXT>
