<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Software Error in Guam Airport Radar System Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- A software error was found in
a Guam airport radar system that might have prevented last week's
deadly crash of a Korean Air jet in Guam, U.S. federal
investigators said today.
</P>
<P>
The FAA Radar Minimum Safe Altitude Warning normally issues an
alert if a jet is flying too low, and officials on the ground
inform the pilot. But U.S. federal investigators said the system
was modified recently and an error apparently was inserted into
the software, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
National Transportation Safety Board investigators said the
software error is not the culprit in Wednesday's crash of Korean
Air Flight 801, which crashed and skidded along a hillside
overlooking Guam International Airport, killing 225 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a cause, it might have possibly been a
prevention," said George Black, an NTSB member.
</P>
<P>
However, the finding is a major piece in the crash. But the
warning system was not the only piece of equipment not operating
on Guam at the time of the crash. The airport's glide slope, which
helps guide the pilot to the runway, was not in service at the
time the plane crashed.
</P>
<P>
The altitude warning system is designed to cover a circular
area with a radius of 63 miles. However, after the software was
modified, it only covered about a mile-wide circular strip that
ran the circumference of the area. Flight 801 was not covered when
it crashed, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Investigators were looking into when the software was altered
and whether only the Guam system was affected.
</P>
<P>
They also were looking at other crucial aspects of the crash,
such as the heavy rain that might be an impact to the crash.
Meanwhile, the NTSB has dispatched officials to Seoul to look at
Korean Air's training methods and the crew records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0033 </DOCNO>
