<HEADLINE> Bubka Wins Men's Pole Vault Gold Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Sergey Bubka of Ukraine won the men's
pole vault world title six times in a row when he sailed over 6.01
meters at the 6th World Athletics Championships here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, he becomes the first person in the world to win
all the titles in the championship history. But the 33-year-old
disappointed the crowd when he gave up his three attacks at the 6.15
meters, one centimeter more than his own world record.
</P>
<P>
The silver medal was won by Maksim Tarasov of Russia at 5.96m and
the bronze went to Dean Starkey of the United States at 5.91m.
</P>
<P>
Bubka, who has broken the world record for 35 times, entered the
meet with a 5.60 meter best this season, but performed brilliantly in
today's final.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov, the 1992 Olympic champion who jumped over 6.00 meters
early this year, was his only challenger. The Russian jumped over
5.96m on his first attempt, but Bubka sailed over 6.01m on his opening
try. With the gold in hand, Bubka intended to beat the record, but
stopped midway on his first attack at 6.15m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
