<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Pessimistic about Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas
today expressed his pessimism about the upcoming second round of
U.N.-sponsored peace talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktas said that the peace talks with the Cypriot government
is bound to fail if Turkish Cypriots' equality and sovereignty is
neglected, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader made the remarks during a stopover in
Istanbul's Ataturk Airport en route to a meeting with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides in the Swiss town of Montreux tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that Turkish Cypriots are determined to defend their
basic rights, Denktas said that the Greek Cypriot side should make
positive steps for the setting up of a bi-zonal federation on the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated his early demand that the Cypriot government
should freeze its accession negotiations with the European Union (EU)
and stop the development of anti-aircraft missile system to be
purchased from Russia.
</P>
<P>
"I think this meeting will be the last one. If no clarity is
reached on these topics, it will be clear that we can go nowhere,"
Denktas said.
</P>
<P>
On the first round of talks with Clerides under the U.N. mediation
near New York from July 9 to 12, Denktas said that there had been a
political setback, or regression, since the talks in New York.
</P>
<P>
Rebuffing the accusations of the Turkey-Northern Cyprus partial
integration accord signed last week, the Turkish Cypriot leader
said that these people should ask how the Cypriot government could
apply to the EU on behalf of the whole island.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Clerides left earlier today for Switzerland to
attend the peace talks with Denktas, according to reports reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish delegation from the Foreign Ministry led by Deputy
Undersecretary Inal Batu will reportedly also fly to the Swiss town of
Montreux to monitor the talks between the two rival communities of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and took over the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive coup by Greek Cypriots who tried to seek union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
For years, the United Nations has been striving for a peaceful
settlement of the thorny issue but no concrete results have been
achieved so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
