<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half Million S. Africans Apply to Join Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 10 (Xinhua) -- More than half a million
people have applied to the South African Police Services (SAPS)
for only one thousand jobs recently advertized by the police, an
official said today.
</P>
<P>
SAPS Human Resources Manager Strini Govender, who is in charge
of the process of recruitment, said the SAPS has received
6189,327 applications to fill the 1,200 jobs recently advertized.
</P>
<P>
The police management is interpreting the situation as a sign
of public confidence in the police force. They have brushed aside
suggestion that this could be a desperate sign of unemployed
people willing to take on any job.
</P>
<P>
Graduates from universities and technical colleges, who are
unable to find employment, are also reportedly trying their luck
with the SAPS.
</P>
<P>
According to Govender, 93.3 percent of the applicants are from
the black population. Colored applicants accounted for 3.3
percent. Indian and white applicants accounted for 1.5 and 1.7
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Govender said the lengthy process of sifting through the
applications to find the right candidates could mean that
successful candidates might start their duties a year from now.
</P>
<P>
"We are currently involved in checking whether applicants
fulfill the basic requirements, which include a matriculation
certificate and a driver's license," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "those without a driver's license will not
qualify for the second phase of the process, which include an
interview, a literacy test, as well as a medical fitness test."
</P>
<P>
At least 40 police personnel have been assigned the task of
sifting through piles of applications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
