<HEADLINE> Former S. Leone Leader Asked to Help Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Former Sierra Leonean leader
Joseph Momoh has been brought back on the political stage for a
peaceful solution to the current crisis as neighboring countries
tightened sanctions against the military junta.
</P>
<P>
Former president Momoh, who himself was overthrown in a coup
five years ago, was called back from exile by ousted president
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah to help restart the failed Abidjan peace
talks, the British Broadcasting Corporation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Momoh was quoted as saying today he hastened to lead a
delegation to neighboring Guinea for talks with President Lansana
Conte.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which was held on Saturday night, helped return all
hopes for peaceful settlement of the Sierra Leone crisis, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are all unhappy with the present situation in the country.
I thought I could use what little remaining influence I have with
the Guinean authorities and with the foreign ministers of the
sub-region to help resolve the present impasse in Sierra Leone in
a peaceful manner," Momoh said.
</P>
<P>
The former president did not mention the outcome of the talks
he had on Saturday night with Guinean authorities, saying he had
to discuss the negotiations with Freetown's military junta leader
Major Johnny Paul Koroma before making anything public.
</P>
<P>
It is not known what effect this move would have on the United
Nations demand for the restoration of power to ousted president
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
But many observers are keen to see what will evolve in the
next few weeks in Sierra Leone's political maze.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Sierra Leone has been tense after the
blockade of the troubled country's land, sea and airspace by the
west African peace-keeping force was tightened in the wake of
Koroma's announcement that the junta will stay in power for four
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
