<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Reach Consensus on Tie-up Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Water experts of Bangladesh and
neighboring India today reached consensus on the construction of a
tie-up embankment on both sides of the common river Teesta,
informed sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The consensus was reached at the Standing Committee of the
Bangladesh-India Joint River Commission (JRC), which today began a
cross-border meeting on Lalmonirhat town, 270 kilometers northwest
of Bangladesh's capital Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The sharing of waters of the Teesta is also being discussed at
the Standing Committee meeting, said the sources, adding that the
two countries share 54 common rivers while both sides last
December signed a 30-year water treaty on sharing Ganges water.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Sunday, the water experts on the JRC inspected the
changed course of the Teesta in Bangladesh's side, to find out the
technical feasibility of an embankment on the right bank of the
common river.
</P>
<P>
The proposed one and half a kilometer embankment will start
from Permekligonj in India and end at the no-man's land near
Kaligonj in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The JRC Standing Committee members are expected to begin
another round of talks at Shiliguri in India on August 12. The JRC
members will visit the Indian Teesta Barrage Project at Bazal Doba
before beginning the two-day meeting, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The Shiliguri meeting is scheduled to finalize the draft
proposal on the construction of the tie-up embankment, the sources
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
