<HEADLINE> France Supports OAU Intervention in Comoran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- France today expressed its support
for the intervention by the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
aimed at finding a "negotiated solution" to the crisis in the
Indian Ocean nation of Comoros.
</P>
<P>
A group of separatists in one of the Comoran islands, Anjouan,
last week declared "independence" and asked for the return of
French rule.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that this intervention (by the OAU) should
create the conditions of a negotiated and lasting solution," said
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutraux.
</P>
<P>
An OAU special envoy, Pierre Yere, held talks with Comoran
President, Mohamed Taki Abdoulakarim, last Saturday and will be in
Anjouan today to talk with the separatists.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that France opposed the use of force by
either side in the Comoros, and respected the territorial
integrity of the island nation.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France had asked the European Union to
increase economic aid to the Comoros to improve the living
condition of the Comoran people.
</P>
<P>
France granted independence to the Comoros in 1975, but has
retained rule in one of its four islands, Mayotte. 
</P>
</TEXT>
