<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Get 16 Billion U.S. Dollars Bail-out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand got a promise today of at
least 16 billion U.S. dollars in financial aid to rebuild its
flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The bail-out will come from international financial
institutions and its Asia-Pacific neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The amount was decided at a one-day international conference
here under the initiative of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF). It was held in a bid to help Thailand recover from its
recent currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the package, the IMF pledged to provide four billion dollars
under a "standby loans" scheme. Japan offered to extend the same
amount in loans through its Export-Import Bank.
</P>
<P>
A total of five billion dollars has been promised by six
economies, with Australia, Hong Kong, Malaysia and Singapore each
pledging one billion dollars, and Indonesia and South Korea 500
million dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The remaining three billion dollars will come from the World
Bank, the Asian Development Bank and China.
</P>
<P>
The funds were medium-term loans maturing in three to five
years at market-based interest rates, Shigemitsu Sugisaki, IMF
deputy managing director who chaired the Tokyo conference, told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral and bilateral loans will be provided soon,
with the IMF Executive Board approving its loans sometime next
week, Sugisaki said.
</P>
<P>
The size of the bail-out is the second largest of its kind,
after Mexico, which received 50 billion dollars in international
financial assistance during the peso crisis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's baht currency has been tumbling since the government
shifted to a floating exchange mechanism on July 2. The Thai
currency crisis also had an adverse impact on other Asian currency
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo conference was attended by 10 countries and economies
from the Asia-Pacific region, including China, Japan, Australia,
Singapore and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
