<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Economy Shows Signs of Recovery: Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' economy is showing
signs of a "relative recovery" this year after its recession in
1996, Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"If unforeseen political developments do not intervene, it
will have better results in 1997 than in 1996," the minister
told reporters after a meeting with the governor of the Central
Bank of Cyprus, the general manager of the Cyprus Development
Bank and some government officials.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 1997 growth rate is expected to be at around
3 percent, compared with 2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rate in 1997 will be around 3.3 to 3.4 percent,
while inflation is expected to be around 3.5 percent,
Christodoulou said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the island's public debt, he noted that it is
expected to be around 54 percent of GDP, while the limit set by
the Maastricht Treaty is 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the island's tourism is also recovering,
the minister indicated that there would be a better performance
in the next three to four months than that in the same period of
1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, around 1,950,000 tourists visited the island, down
from 2.1 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on speculation in the local press concerning the
liberalization of the island's financial system, Christodoulou
said that it would proceed as scheduled, adding that it would
take place before Cyprus' accession negotiations with the
European Union start.
</P>
<P>
"The liberalization would be concluded by March 1998," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for full EU membership in 1990. The EU has
reaffirmed that accession negotiations with Cyprus will begin
early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
