<HEADLINE> Businessmen Confess to Payments to President's Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Two businessmen today admitted
having paid Kim Hyun-chul, the second son of South Korean
President Kim Young-sam, money for favors.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old junior Kim was arrested on May 17 on charge of
tax evasion, and for having taken at least 3.6 million
U.S. dollars in return for favors from two business firms.
</P>
<P>
However, Kim Hyun-chul rejected the accusations, arguing that
the money was given under the name of "operational funds" or
"political donations."
</P>
<P>
In a hearing on suspected irregularities involving Kim
Hyun-chul Monday in the Seoul Court, Kim Tok-yong, chairman of the
Dooyang Group, indirectly testified that he had given the junior
Kim money, and asked for his influence in a civil suit.
</P>
<P>
The other businessman, Lee Song-ho, former president of Daeho
Construction Company, said he had asked Kim Hyun-chul to influence
an application for a cable television business license.
</P>
<P>
Lee confessed that he had given Kim Hyun-chul a total of two
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Local observers said the confessions of the two businessmen
would help the prosecution verify the charges of irregularities by
Kim. 
</P>
