<HEADLINE> Top Yamaichi Executives Step Down Over Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- As many as 11 top executives of
Japan's fourth largest brokerage, Yamaichi Securities, resigned
from their posts today to take responsibility for the unfolding
scandal involving payoffs to a Sokaiya corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
The resigned include Yamaichi Securities Company Chairman
Tsuguo Yukihira, President Atsuo Miki, five vice presidents and
four directors.
</P>
<P>
The resignations came 12 days after Yamaichi was raided by
Tokyo prosecutors searching for evidence to substantiate
suspicions that 79 million yen (680,000 U.S. dollars) was funneled
to racketeer Ryuichi Koike in 1995 as compensation for his
investment losses.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi's reshuffle follows similar moves by Nomura Securities
Company -- Japan's largest brokerage -- and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank,
one of the country's largest commercial banks, which have also
been involved in payoff scandals involving Koike.
</P>
<P>
Nomura and Dai-Ichi Kangyo have already been forced to suspend
some of their business operations as administrative punishment for
their illegal actions. 
</P>
