<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Militia Demobilization Program Well Underway in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The first militia
demobilization program which started late last month in the Lower
Shabelle region of southern Somalia is running smoothly and
successfully.
</P>
<P>
The program, the first of its kind, has demobilized more than
150 militiamen in a rehabilitation center inside the port town of
Merca, 100 km south of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
All weapons belonging to the militiamen were collected before
enrolling them in the camp where they are given different
lectures including English and basic arithmetic in the first six
months while those who survive their civil education program will
be rewarded with vocational training techniques including proper
farming.
</P>
<P>
According to Zakaria Mohamed Sheikh, one of the 11 teachers at
the Merca Militia Rehabilitation Center, the project is sponsored
by the Italian aid agency COSV and the women group of IIDA with
the collaboration of Hussein Mohamed Aidid's regional security
officials.
</P>
<P>
The project, funded by the European Union office for Somalia,
will last for a year, Zakaria said.
</P>
<P>
The center, headed by Professor Ibrahim Hirsi Aden, former
geology rector of Somalia's National University, provides full
accommodation, food, medicine, launderette for the clothes of the
militiamen and little pocket money exceeding 350,000 Somali
shillings equivalent to 41 U.S. Dollars for each student per
month.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the ordinary lessons, the militiamen are also
taught different lessons on sports and arts.
</P>
<P>
The demobilized militiamen are not allowed to chew khat or
smoke cigarettes during the six-day programs of each week. They
are given a brief holiday of 24 hours every Friday to visit their
families.
</P>
<P>
The demobilization is not only beneficial for the ordinary
citizens whose security is improved with increasing number of
demobilized militiamen, but for the families of the gunmen who
are now receiving this little non-blood stained money.
</P>
<P>
According to the administration of the center, there are quite
a large number of militiamen from the capital and the surrounding
districts applying for the center.
</P>
<P>
"Our resources are limited at the time being, but we're
hopeful that the program will be extended later," Zakaria noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
