<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Drug Addiction Means Jail Term in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Two months ago, 43-year-old
Abdullah had never believed his hashish addiction could bring him
to prison, but he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
Spending most of his time in a 1.5-meter-wide, two-meter-long
room in a Sharjah prison in the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the
Pakistani engineer is serving his first jail sentence in his
life. He received a one-year jail term two months ago because of
drug use.
</P>
<P>
"I used hashish during a brief holiday but had no idea I
could be imprisoned in the UAE," he told reporters dispiritedly.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested after being found his blood was positive
after addicting hashish. Doctors said hashish and valium could
remain detectable for up to two weeks while hard narcotics such
as heroin and cocaine could linger for up to two months in man's
circulatory system.
</P>
<P>
Under a new UAE anti-drug law issued last year, those who
take, in any way, drugs or psychotropical substances in the UAE
shall be penalized by sentences of one to four years depending
on the drug involved.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah was not the only one who was put into jail because of
drug use. Many others are serving prison terms for the same
offense in UAE prisons.
</P>
<P>
A young Australian woman who was sentenced to four years in
prison when traces of marijuana were detected in her urine. The
25-year-old woman who admitted smoking the drug in Sri Lanka is
awaiting for an appeal against her conviction in a Sharjah
court.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. diplomat here confirmed that four U.S. citizens living
in the UAE are serving sentences in the Dubai jail after
consuming drugs overseas and having been tested positive upon
their return.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers in the UAE said drug use was treated very seriously
in the Gulf country, but they suggested the anti-drug law could
enforce rehabilitation instead of jail.
</P>
<P>
"The laws on drugs here are one of the best of their kind in
the world," said Salim, a lawyer in Abu Dhabi, "the law shows
little sympathy toward drug dealers. For the sake of the
protection of society, the death penalty will be applied to those
promoting and dealing in drugs."
</P>
<P>
"But the authorities could send the abusers for treatment
instead of jail on the basis of some people being patients
rather than criminals," he suggested.
</P>
<P>
Police officers did not agree with the opinion. They are
launching a nation-wide war against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
"How could drug dealers find a market? A place with many drug
addictors is the most suitable one," said captain Safi Bitar
from Abu Dhabi Police Station.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to eliminate the drug market is to lessen the
number of drug users. Hash punishments are always effective," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He may be right. Many drug users who are serving jail terms
in prison have said they would never thought about hashish or
heroin again.
</P>
<P>
"While I have found out the hardest way possible, I just want
other people to know this can happen and to be careful because I
has ruined my life," Abdullah said regretfully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
