<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Minister Assures Good Price for Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian government will
formulate reasonable policies to enable farmers to sell their
crops at good prices, the Minister for the Agro-Industrial Complex
(AIC), Yuri Karasyk, said today.
</P>
<P>
Karasyk made the remarks because of farmers' worry about
possible lower selling prices than production costs for their
crops.
</P>
<P>
However, the AIC minister admitted that the current advance
price for third grade wheat stood at only 270 hryvnas (about 148
U.S. dollars) per ton, while fifth grade was priced at 214 hryvnas
(about 118 dollars) per ton. These prices could hardly cover the
production costs.
</P>
<P>
The final prices for grain should be high enough to cover the
production costs and allow farmers to earn reasonable profits,
Karasyk noted.
</P>
<P>
State policies on prices would be worked out after the grain
harvest, he added.
</P>
<P>
By August 10, more than 60 percent of cereals and beans had
been reaped. Karasyk was fairly optimistic that reaping of crops
would be completed by mid-August.
</P>
<P>
At present, prices for agricultural products in Ukraine are
largely dependent on the level of mechanization of agriculture,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He called for leasing of agricultural machines to farmers as a
possible way out of the crisis of shortage of machines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
