<HEADLINE> Gold Price Future Still Gloomy: Analysts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Australian gold analysts are
still less than optimistic about the future of gold despite a
moderate price improvement since early this month.
</P>
<P>
The spot gold price slid to 315.60 U.S. dollars an ounce in
early July after news that the Reserve Bank of Australia sold off
two thirds of its gold stocks.
</P>
<P>
After several price fluctuations, it was trading at 327.05
dollars this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Norm Miskelly from Paul Morgan Securities was quoted by the
Australian Associated Press as saying that he expected the gold
price to continue to move sideways for quite some time into the
future, as there was a worldwide oversupply of gold together with
only moderate demand.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not expect the spot price to drop below 300
dollars, nor to move above 340 dollars within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
He believed gold was now less a financial instrument and viewed
instead as a commodity, and as a result has shared the drop in
prices other commodities had experienced.
</P>
<P>
Nic Dinham, a Porter Western gold analyst, said gold would
remain vulnerable to continued central bank sales.
</P>
<P>
A lot of European Union participants were selling their gold
stocks off, but there were still some big countries showing
interest in gold, he said.
</P>
<P>
Analyst Ted Leschke from BZW Australia Ltd said the gold price
is continuing to suffer under hedge funds deliberately forcing
down the price.
</P>
<P>
Other analysts based in Sydney said gold was no longer regarded
as a monetary tool and its future looks poor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
