<HEADLINE> France: Congo Republic Fighting "Unacceptable" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- France today described the renewed
fighting in Brazzaville, capital of the Congo Republic, as
"unacceptable," and deplored the breakdown of the ceasefire signed
by the two warring factions on July 13.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux said: "It is
again for Congolese parties to put an end to the hostilities and
agree rapidly on a political accord under the auspices of Gabonese
President Omar Bongo and Mohamed Sahnoun, the representative of
the OAU (Organization of African Unity) and the United Nations for
the Great Lakes region."
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. Security Council would not send a
peacekeeping force to Brazzaville until a political agreement was
reached between the two warring sides, and a ceasefire observed.
</P>
<P>
The troops loyal to Congolese President Pascal Lissouba and
militias controlled by former President Denis Sassou Nguesso have
used artillery and other heavy weapons in a new round of fighting
which began on August 7. Reports said there had been heavy
casualties to civilians in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 people have been killed since fighting began in
Brazzaville on June 5 between the two rival factions, while
negotiations mediated by Bongo and Sahnoun in Libreville have
failed to produce concrete results.
</P>
<P>
The French Ambassador to Brazzaville, Raymond Cesaire, who is
one of the few foreign envoys holding out there, said on Sunday
that he did not plan to quit the city. He urged the parties to
seek a political solution to the conflict with "diplomatic
tenacity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
