<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defects Seen in Phare Aid Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A global evaluation of the
Phare aid program, the first since its launching in early 1990, has
discovered defects within the program, a European Commission press
release said today.
</P>
<P>
An evaluation submitted to the European Parliament has shown
fragmentation of effort and lack of leverage in implementing Phare
(Program of Aid for Central and Eastern Europe).
</P>
<P>
The program, set up after the Group of Seven summit in
July 1989, provides assistance to central and eastern European
countries for their reform in the sectors of transport, energy and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
"Its effectiveness and impact have been diluted by lack of
leverage to ensure good program performance, by deficiencies in
project cycle management and by a preoccupation with financial and
procedural control to the detriment of substantive program design
and performance," the release said.
</P>
<P>
The evaluation, however, showed that the Phare had also shown
"remarkable flexibility in addressing the different needs of the
partner countries, which have embarked on transition from
different starting points with different paces."
</P>
<P>
The evaluation, drawn up by independent consultants, was based
on monitoring and assessing Phare's relevance, appropriateness,
impact, effectiveness, sustainability and efficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
