<HEADLINE> Annan's U.N. Reform Gets Support From 16 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan accepted a formal statement of support from 16
countries on reform within the U.N., in Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued today by the U.N. Office at Geneva
(UNOG) said the statement was presented on Sunday by Swedish Prime
Minister Goran Persson.
</P>
<P>
Persson's predecessor, Ingvar Carlsson, convinced the 16
countries -- Australia, Brazil, Canada, Cote d'Ivoire, the Czech
Republic, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Ireland, Jamaica, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, Mexico, the Netherlands, South Africa, and
Sweden -- in 1995 to encourage U.N. reform, on the occasion of the
U.N. 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16 countries described the U.N. reform package
proposed by Annan in July as "timely," and deserving of "full
support" of their governments.
</P>
<P>
"There is an opportunity to take real and substantive steps
forward. That opportunity should not be missed," they were quoted
by the UNOG release as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time to go from words to deeds," the statement
said. "Let's empower the United Nations to confront, through
collective action, the global challenges of the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed thanks to Persson for the statement, which he
saw as a sign of growing government support for his proposals.
</P>
</TEXT>
