<HEADLINE> China's Largest Oilfield Adds one Billion Tons Of Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Daqing Oilfield, China's
largest, recently added one billion tons of oil reserves, meaning
another 15 years of high oil yields in the old oilfield in
Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
It began production in the 1960s, and after three decades, its
proven reserves are 5.26 billion tons, 4.65 billion tons of which
have already been tapped. It has drilled 30,312 oil and water
wells.
</P>
<P>
In 1976, annual output went above the 50 million ton mark, a
peak, and 56 million tons in 1994, and the output has kept at that
level for three years. Its output in 1996 accounted for 35.6
percent of China's total.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, Daqing's aggregate crude oil output was
1.46 billion tons, 47 percent of China's total continental oil
output. In the first six months of this year, 27.79 million tons
of crude oil were produced, with an industrial output value of
25.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Daqing Oil Management Bureau is China's No.1 industrial
conglomerate. Its long-term development has reduced the number of
blow-out wells and water-injection and polymer flooding have been
used to ensure steady production.
</P>
<P>
Its goal for the next 15 years is to become a multinational oil
syndicate and by 2010 to increase sales and profit to three times
the 1995 amount.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
