<HEADLINE> HK Participates in Financing Package for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has decided to
contribute to a financing package organized by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to assist Thailand in making economic
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), the
package was agreed at a meeting organized by the IMF in Tokyo
today.
</P>
<P>
An HKMA spokesman said that at the request of the IMF,
participants agreed to a financing package totaling 16 billion
U.S. dollars including one billion dollars from Hong Kong, four
billion US dollars from the IMF and the rest from Japan,
Australia, Singapore, South Korea and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Lending to Thailand will take the form of a medium-term loan at
market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Donald Tsang, financial secretary and controller of the Hong
Kong Exchange Fund, said that Hong Kong is committed to regional
monetary stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that the recent spate of speculative attacks has caused
volatility of various degrees in the currency markets of Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Although the Hong Kong dollar has not been affected, the
likely contagion effect is very real," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is in Hong Kong's interests as a leading
financial center in the region to see a strong and stable
neighboring environment.
</P>
<P>
HKMA Chief Executive Joseph Yam who represented Hong Kong's
financial secretary at the Tokyo meeting said that Hong Kong's
participation in the financing package to Thailand will contribute
to the overall financial stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that participants saw the meeting as a historical
crossroads in regional financial cooperation, and possibly as a
precursor of standing arrangements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
