<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pigs Heart Transplants for Humans Possible in 5 to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Pig hearts and kidneys could be
transplanted into humans within five to 10 years, a senior
cardiologist said today.
</P>
<P>
Venom from the deadly cobra snake may be the secret ingredient
that allows the breakthrough to happen, said Peter MacDonald, an
associate professor at the University of New South Wales.
</P>
<P>
he said an acute shortage of human donors had forced
researchers to examine using pig hearts in transplant patients.
</P>
<P>
The major hurdle was stopping the human immune system rejecting
the pig heart through a violent reaction where antibodies
immediately started killing pig cells.
</P>
<P>
"There's a very powerful and rapid rejection response that
occurs within minutes of transplanting a pig organ into a human,"
MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
"The cobra venom factor is a derivative of cobra venom and what
it does is take out one of the key steps that starts this
hyper-rejection response, interrupting the whole process," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
MacDonald said researchers had already conducted experiments
where rats had survived for a month after receiving guinea pig
hearts.
</P>
<P>
"They might sound like fairly close species but the rat has
pre-formed antibodies against the guinea pig in much the same way
that the human does against the larger pig," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pig hearts were the most compatible with humans because of
their size, the professor added.
</P>
<P>
"Given the development in this area, I think it would be
clinically feasible to do this type of transplant within the next
5 to 10 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Professor MacDonald will present his findings to the Cardiac
Society of Australia and New Zealand annual meeting on Wednesday
in Hobart, Tasmania island off mainland Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
