Philippines, on their second meeting with Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen on August 2 in Phnom Penh, Philippine Foreign Minister
Domingo Siazon, chairman of the special meeting, told reporters at
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement after the meeting, which lasted about four
hours, the foreign ministers said that as a result of the
briefing, and the discussions that followed, they "agreed that
ASEAN will remain engaged in its efforts to help restore political
stability in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also discussed the latest developments in
Cambodia, including the appointment of Foreign Minister Ung Huot
as First Prime Minister, and assessed these developments in the
context of their implications and impact on the continuing efforts
to restore political stability in Cambodia, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN will continue to carefully monitor further
developments," they said, adding that the question of recognition
of Foreign Minister Ung Huot as First Prime Minister did not arise
at the meeting "because ASEAN member states recognize states not
governments."
</P>
<P>
The ministers also said that the timing of Cambodia's admission
into ASEAN was not on the agenda of the special meeting.
</P>
<P>
As to the form in which ASEAN will pursue its efforts, the
foreign ministers agreed that it need not necessarily be limited
to direct meetings at the Prime Ministers level on the Cambodia
side, and at the various capitals, but could also proceed at the
level of the foreign ministers at various other places, such as
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of organizing an informal meeting, involving
all parties directly concerned, is also not to be excluded, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Explaining their assignment division of work, in order to
follow up the developments in Cambodia, Siazon said Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas will be in contact with Ung Huot,
while Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasan will be contacting
Prince Norodom Ranariddh and his group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
