<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Young Scientists In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences
(Cast) announced today that it will increase the number of young
scientists it employs a great deal this year for the country's
21st century scientific development drive.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yongxiang, the academy's new president, said that this will
satisfy the country's need for new scientists in the next
century. It will add 100 young scientists each year and put them
in responsible positions in key projects.
</P>
<P>
The young scientists must be below 40 and should have a
Ph.D. degree with at least two years' post-doctoral research. Lu
said they will receive financial and equipment assistance from the
academy and the research institutes that employ them.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six institutes have promised to spend at least one
million yuan (about 125,000 US dollars) each in the scientists'
research, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The academy will assess the work of the employed scientists
after three years, Lu noted, saying that those incompetent will be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
More than a half of the academy's research institutes have
vacancies for young scientists, 46 of which are in Beijing and
Shanghai, Cast sources said.
</P>
<P>
The academy plans to release its detailed employment plan in
overseas Chinese embassies and consulates and on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
