<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Targets 75 Naira to One Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has set
an exchange rate target of 75 Naira to one U.S. dollar by the end
of the year, compared to a rate of 83.2 Naira to one dollar at
present, The Vanguard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a competent finance ministry source as
saying that the decision is one of the tools of macro-economic
management adopted by the government for resuscitating the
economy.
</P>
<P>
It is also based on the success in the exchange market in the
first half of 1997, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, the Nigerian currency Naira
has been revaluating from 85 Naira to one dollar consistently to
83.3 Naira to one dollar at present, at the autonomous foreign
exchange market operated by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
However, the sharp rise for dollars at the market in the last
few weeks has put the government target at risk, even though the
central bank's increasing the rate of treasure bills has helped
in mopping up some of the funds, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to it, the government has also set a target of a
single digit inflation.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Nigeria's inflation rate declined
from 28 percent in December last year to 17.5 percent in June.
The targets are 15.5 percent for July and 13.8 for August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
