<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Rejects U.N. Census Estimation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has rejected a U.N
estimation that its population reached 120 million, insisting
that the biggest African country's population is 104.2 million.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Champion today quoted Lieutenant-Colonel Charis
Ugokwe, chairman of the National Population Commission as saying
that the estimate by the United Nations agencies was based on the
growth rate from the faulty 1963 census figure.
</P>
<P>
They should use the results of the country's 1991 census,
which indicated a population of 88,992,220 and an annual growth
rate of 2.83 percent, he continued, adding that the mistake was
deliberate.
</P>
<P>
The chairman admitted that there are controversies concerning
the census, noting they were mainly concerning those abroad who
were not counted.
</P>
<P>
He also quoted the examples of the United Kingdom and Germany,
saying that there is no census that is not controversial.
</P>
<P>
Ugokwe denied that Nigeria is over-populated or that the
population is growing faster than necessary, though he recognized
the need for control so that over-population will not occur.
</P>
<P>
He explained that while there has been an improvement in the
registration of child births by Nigerians, the registration of
deaths is still a problem as people do not care to do it.
</P>
<P>
He added that his commission has started preparations for the
2001 census. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
