<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Structure Improving (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China's economic structure,
mainly that of its industries, has been improving in the past six
years especially since the 14th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The improvement has been marked by a steady transition and the
switch from light to heavy industrialization, according to a
recent report by the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
China's gross national product (GNP) increased at an average
rate of 12.1 percent annually during the period, with the primary
industry rising by 4.7 percent in value-added output, the
secondary industry by 17.1 percent, and the service sector by 9.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of the value-added output produced by the three
industries changed from 24.5, 42.1, 33.4 in 1991, to 20, 48.9,
31.1 in 1996. The employment figure increased by 40.51 million,
with a rise of 3.13 million in the secondary industry, 56.54
million in the service sector, but a drop of 39.16 million in the
primary industry.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said these changes represent the speedy progress
of the country's effort to industrialize itself, with the
secondary industry, especially the industrial sector, becoming the
major contributor to the economy.
</P>
<P>
Of the total value-added output in 1996, the secondary industry
accounted for more than half, 85.2 percent of which came from
industrial production. During the six years, production in the
primary and service sectors fell by 6.8 percent, while the
secondary industry increased by the same percentage.
</P>
<P>
The steady rise of the secondary industry in the nation's
economy, most notably a sustainable and rapid increase of
industrial production, indicates that China's industrialization
has become more advanced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
