<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Structure Improving (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The proportion of heavy industry in industrial production has
been growing steadily, standing at 53.9 percent last year and
representing a shift from a system dominated by light industry in
the 1980s to present-day heavy industry-oriented structure.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six years, both the output value ratio between
the three industries and that of their own has been greatly
improved. Although the primary industry's proportion has declined
somewhat, the total agricultural supply and demand has maintained
a level growth.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the practice of diversifying businesses in rural
areas has proved successful, with animal husbandry and fisheries
playing a bigger role in these regions.
</P>
<P>
The service sector has become a leader in employing surplus
labor forces, while the booming real estate, banking and insurance
fields are promoting the diversification of the sector and moving
it to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report also pointed out four problems that have
surfaced in China's economic structure:
</P>
<P>
-- Agriculture remains the weak link in the national economy;
</P>
<P>
-- The industrial sector, though a major contributor, needs to
make internal improvements;
</P>
<P>
-- The service sector is relatively inefficient, its internal
structure needs to be revamped, and more importantly, the total
supply and demand is insufficient; and
</P>
<P>
-- Regional industrial structures are developing in a copycat
fashion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
