<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Stock Market Active in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's stock market recorded
an impressive performance in the first half of the year, in terms
of market capitalization, all-share index, deals, turnover and
foreign portfolio investment, The Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a release of the Nigerian stock exchange on Friday
as saying that the total value of securities listed on the
exchange appreciated by 33 percent in the first six months to
stand at 380.5 billion Naira (about 4.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was compared to 285.6 billion Naira (about 3.4 billion
dollars) at the begining of the year and an increase of 29
percent in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, a total of 31,710 deals for 672.5 million
shares worth of 5.8 billion Naira (about 69 million dollars) were
executed on the six trading floors of the exchange, namely in
Lagos, Kaduna, Ibadan, Port Harcourt and two other cities.
</P>
<P>
The release attributed the buoyant trading to the introduction
of a central securities clearing system.
</P>
<P>
The exchange's all-share index stood at 8,459.29, 21 percent
up from the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
"The Nigerian stock market remains attractive to foreign
portfolio investors who are now going beyond inquiries to
actually invest in the market," the release said.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, foreign currency transactions valued at 8.6
million dollars have been effected, 79.2 percent more than the
4.8 million dollars in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, the exchange approved eight new
issues with a total market value of 1.2 billion Naira (about 14
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
