<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Catch Wall Street Chill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
followed the lead of Wall Street to close sharply lower as sellers
sought to avoid the downward U.S. outlook and the local bond
market faltered.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 44.2 points or 1.63
percent at 2,667.2 after Wall Street fell almost two percent on
Friday night as a result of profit-taking prompted by inflation
fears.
</P>
<P>
"The market has reacted to Wall Street today and there was
quite a bit of selling in the mid-afternoon," Clint Smith from
Peake Lands Kirwan said.
</P>
<P>
"This market has three or four weeks to run and I can see
another 40 points off the market," Stuart Smith from Henderson
Charlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 82.8 points to 4,301.0, with
News Corp, one of the major casualties, and ordinary shares down
15 cents at 5.92 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector fell generally in line with the market.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 34 cents, Westpac Bank was 10
cents lower, ANZ dropped 21 cents while Commonwealth Bank was 17
cents lower.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 12.3 points to 1,392.1, but
bellwether BHP was surprisingly light in trade and avoided the
market dip despite recent boardroom upheaval.
</P>
<P>
BHP recovered from an early morning low of 16.7 to close two
cents firmer at 17.01 on turnover of 5.7 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks stood out against the market, with the index rising
5.3 points to 1,288.9 and bullion closing at 326.55 US dollars per
ounce compared to Friday's close of 322.05 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 294.08 million shares worth 836.16
million Australian dollars (614.57 million US dollars) with falls
more than doubling rises by 792 to 377.  
</P>
</TEXT>
