<HEADLINE> New UN Team to Check Iraqi Armament Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A new U.N. team belonging to
the U.N. Special Commision charged with eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction will check Iraq's former armament
programs.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources here said today that the 12-member team, which
arrived here Saturday, held two meetings with those employed in
the Baghdad Permanent Monitoring and Verification Center. But they
did not mention whether the team will visit any Iraqi sites.
</P>
<P>
It is the second U.N. team specializing in biological weapons to
visit Iraq since July 27.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the new U.N. team will leave Baghdad next
Friday for Bahrain en route to New York City.
</P>
<P>
New chairman of the U.N. Special Commission Richard Butler
had announced before leaving Baghdad on July 25 that he will
return to Iraq once again in a month to continue his talks with
Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. It made the lift of the sanctions on the
precondition that Iraq should destroy its weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
