<HEADLINE> Malaysia Seeks Investment Safety in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said today it
would participate in the reconstruction of Bosnia-Herzegovina but
added that the Malaysian private sector is still not very
confident in Bosnia's stability at present time.
</P>
<P>
During talks with visiting Co-Chairmen of the Council of
Ministers of Bosnia Haris Siladjzic and Boro Bosic, Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad sought an assurance from the
Bosnian government that Malaysians' businesses and investments in
the Balkan state will be safeguarded and given attention by the
authorities there, Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad
Badawi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir in the talks also expressed the hope that all
conditions under the Dayton Peace Accord on Bosnia would be met by
all parties in the Balkan state, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir told the two Bosnian leaders that it was essential for
all factions to observe the peace accord to ensure that the
situation in Bosnia return to normal and the peace and political
stability prevail, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed that if this could be achieved, it
would be easier for Bosnia to obtain assistance like investment
and cooperation in the economic field and forge ties in trade and
other fields with the international community including Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir asked the Bosnian government to take positive measures
to further boost the confidence of Malaysian businessmen so that
they would increase the volume of their investment there.
</P>
<P>
The two Bosnian leaders said it was the desire of Bosnia to
provide protection besides encouraging investments from abroad in
line with efforts to forge trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said both Siladjzic and Bosic agreed that their
country should learn from Malaysia's experience.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has identified assistance for projects worth 12
million ringgit (about 4.6 million U.S. dollars) to be implemented
around the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo. The projects are expected
to be completed within a year. Several projects related to health
and agriculture would be launched in a few months, according to
officials here.
</P>
<P>
The two Bosnian leaders arrived here Sunday for a four-day
visit to Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
