<HEADLINE> KAL Crash Results in Cancellation of Overseas Trips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The tragic crash of a South Korean
Air (KAL) plane in Guam, the United States, has resulted in
increasing cancellations of South Korean travellers' overseas
trips, according to an investigation by the Ministry of Culture
and Sports.
</P>
<P>
Of 54,450 South Koreans who made reservations for oveaseas
trips at the nation's top 15 travel agencies to the end of this
month, 2,927 surveyed have scratched their plans in the wake of
the KAL crash.
</P>
<P>
"In our survey on reservation cancellations after the mishap,
the cancellation rate stood at about 5.4 percent," the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry pointed out that the cancellation rate, which
means five out of every 100 of travelers cancelled their
schedules, is considerably high, given that August is the apex of
the tourist season.
</P>
<P>
It was analysed that the travelers who cancelled their plans
apprently fear they could be the next victim of an air accident.
</P>
<P>
A KAL Boeing 747 plane with 254 on board crashed and burned on
August 6 in Guam. Only about 30 have survived the crash.
</P>
<P>
The trend of cancellation is expected to continue for the time
being as shockwaves are felt nationwide from the KAL tragedy, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
