<HEADLINE> Tomb from New Stone Age Discovered in Henan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered a 6,000-year-old tomb at a construction site in Zhoukou
prefecture in central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Built during the Neolithic (New Stone) Age, the tomb was found
two meters underground. Skeletal remains of one body were
unearthed from the 2.5-meter-long and 1.2 meter-wide tomb.
</P>
<P>
Also found in the tomb were polished black pottery pots, bowls,
small grey clay jars, red clay jars, bone needles and some other
cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the black pots and grey jars are still intact
and are of great historical and artistic value.  
</P>
</TEXT>
