<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Cellular Phone Industry Grows Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Cellular telephones are
penetrating the densely populated townships in South Africa,
providing a quick and effective way to reach the millions of
people, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The cellular phones are made available through a community
phone program run by MTN and Vodacom, the industry giants in the
country. As part of their contracts, the government requires the
two companies to provide facilities to under-privileged areas and
to charge subsidized rates to consumers, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Cellular telephones were introduced to South Africa in 1994.
Since then they have proved so successful that they rival the
rate of fixed telephones.
</P>
<P>
The cellular phone industry has attained one million
subscribers in the past three years, which is among the highest
growth rates in the world, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to achievement in the cellular phone industry, the
state-owned telephone company Telkom has also rolled out four
million lines to South Africans since 1994.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is believed to be the most developed country in
telecommunication industry in Africa. Nonetheless, many of South
Africa's 37.9 million people have never made a phone call, let
alone owned one.
</P>
<P>
On average, there are about 10 telephone lines per 100 people
in South Africa. However in the affluent areas, the rate can be
as high as 45 lines per 100 people as against the 0.1 line per
100 people in the impoverished rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Telkom has vowed to spend between 7.82 billion and 11.7
billion U.S. Dollars on expanding the network. The plan will
include doubling connections to 9.3 million lines by the year
2005.
</P>
<P>
About 120,000 public telephones are within this blueprint and
1.7 million lines are targeted for rural consumers, said Mac
Geschwind, chief operating official of Telkom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
