<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian to Accelerate Development of Rural Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Fujian Province in east China has
mapped out a plan to boost the development of rural enterprises,
the local economic pillar.
</P>
<P>
From now to the year 2000, the value-added output of the rural
enterprises is expected to increase by an average of 15 percent
annually and ultimately reach 140 billion yuan (about 16.87
billion US dollars), according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the value-added industrial output is to come to 93
billion yuan (about 1.12 billion US dollars), with that of exports
standing at 100 billion yuan (about 1.20 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
To make this happen, Fujian will allocate 50 million yuan
(about 6.02 million US dollars) in funding for the upgrading of
the rural enterprises, and will give them an additional five
million yuan (about 602,400 US dollars) every year.
</P>
<P>
The property rights system now operating in the rural
enterprises will be overhauled, with large companies changing into
limited liability corporations and small ones becoming cooperative
shareholding companies.
</P>
<P>
The government is encouraging the enterprises to use foreign
capital to improve major products.
</P>
<P>
Fujian also will allocate five million yuan (about 602,400 US
dollars) to the enterprises for technological renovation, and is
urging them to use advanced equipment and establish their own
research institutes.
</P>
<P>
Rural enterprises got their start in Fujian 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the total output value of the rural
enterprises in the province had reached 293.063 billion yuan
(about 35.308 billion US dollars) and the total exports hit 54.84
billion yuan (about 7.089 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
One-third of the total value-added output of the province and
three-fifths of the income of the farmers came from rural
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
