<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artificial Rain Brings Relief to Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- By the end of July, artificial
rainfall had brought more than 200 million cu m of precipitation
to the upper reaches of the Yellow River in northwest China's
Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
Drought conditions since the 1990s have sharply decreased the
flow volume of the Yellow River, China's second longest river,
affecting the economic development and lives of the residents
living on the riverbanks.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Meteorological Bureau has been working with the
Qinghai Power Bureau since late April to produce rain by
artificial means in an area of 30,000 sq km along the upper
reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
When weather conditions are suitable for rainfall, chemicals
can be released into the clouds by plane.
</P>
<P>
The rainmaking operation is expected to last until the end of
September. Its goal is to increase precipitation by 480 million cu
m, about 2.2 percent of the yearly flow of the river across
Qinghai Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Wipes out Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
recorded a 42 billion Kwacha (about 32 million U.S. Dollars)
budget surplus for the second quarter of the year compared to
12.5 billion Kwacha (about 9.6 million dollars) budget deficit in
the first quarter, the Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Finance Minister Ronald Penza as
explaining that there was a remarkable improvement in the
collection of value added tax (VAT) while import tax collection
had also increased.
</P>
<P>
He said 34 billion Kwacha (about 26 million dollars) was
collected in the second quarter in customs duty as against 22.8
billion Kwacha (about 17.5 million dollars) in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Excise duty, domestic VAT, fees and fines collections also
showed dramatic improvement which accounted for the positive
budget surplus during the second quarter, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed his concern over the huge civil service
wage bill which may disturb the budget, but explained that
besides salaries, the government is capable of paying other perks
to be awarded to public workers if the system is managed well.
</P>
<P>
A quarterly report by the Zambia Chambers of Commerce and
Industry indicates that the most notable domestic expenditure
during the second quarter of this year was that of wages and
salaries totaling 88.8 billion Kwacha (about 68 million dollars)
compared to 65.9 billion Kwacha (about 50.7 million dollars)
during the first three months.
</P>
<P>
"Should the Civil Servants Union of Zambia clinch another
salary increase during their anticipated wage talks with the
government this year, the total wage bill will go through the
roof," Penza said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
