<HEADLINE> Zambian Mine Owners to Pay More for Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Electricity Supply
Corporation (ZESCO) will not allow the current subsidized rate to
mines to continue, according to Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the mining firms to take over Zambia Consolidated
Copper Mines (ZCCM) which are currently on sale will have to pay
about 75 percent more for their electricity consumption.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Water and Energy Minister Suresh
Desai as saying on Sunday that the ZCCM consumes about 70 percent
of the country's electricity and has so far been paying
uneconomic rates for power which has adversely affected ZESCO
operations, forcing it to charge high rates for domestic
consumers.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that once the new owners of the mines take over,
ZESCO will charge realistic tariffs and reduce tariffs on
domestic users and agricultural sector. 
