<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberian Cabinet Complete, Awaiting Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- President Charles Taylor of
Liberia has completed the building of the 19-member cabinet of
his new government with Sunday's nomination of the last minister.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, Taylor appointed
Fineboy Darkiwah as minister of health and social welfare,
putting the final touch to cabinet establishment.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said the newly installed 26-member
senate would have to confirm all the nominations made so far
although all are said to have been on the job already.
</P>
<P>
It is anticipated that all the nominees will pass the senate
hearing, the time for which is unknown presently, as Taylor's
National Patriotic Party (NPP) has 21 of the 26 seats in the
senate.
</P>
<P>
Taylor has also nominated five other NPP persons to posts with
cabinet member equivalence, including governor of the central
bank, commissioner of maritime affairs, and managing directors of
Liberia telecommunications corporation, forestry development
authority and Liberia electricity corporation.
</P>
<P>
Among the 19 ministers named, at least three are Taylor's
former rivals in the seven-year civil war, and their inclusion is
seen as a sign of Taylor's promise to forge unity and encourage
reconciliation in the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also consists of at least six persons who had
served in previous governments from William Tolbert's regime to
the Ruth Perry-led council of state, the provisional ruling body
before Yaylor's inauguration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report from Monrovia, capital of Liberia, quoted
a spokesman for Taylor as saying that the president is planning
state funeral for former president Tolbert who was killed in a
military coup in 1980.
</P>
<P>
There is also report that Taylor is to re-bury former
president Samuel Doe, the leader of the 1980 coup who later was
tortured to death during the bitter civil war triggered by
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
The reported funeral is also regarded as part of the efforts
for post-war reconciliation after Taylor's overwhelming victory
in last month's election.
</P>
<P>
But Taylor's critics have pointed out that re-burying could
not be the most important task the warlord-turned president could
utilize time, money and energy on.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders in the country were said to have equally
criticized Taylor's appointments into cabinet positions, saying
that his choice of ministers does not have national spread.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they said that the plan for proportional
representation in the legislature has been messed up by the size
of Taylor's party.
</P>
<P>
The opposition warned that the new president's policies should
be tailored towards encouraging Liberians rather than further
frustrateing them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
