<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Group of Ancient Tombs Found in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-four ancient tombs
dating from the Han Dynasty about 2,000 years ago have been
located at a highway construction site by archaeologists in
northeast China's Liaoning province.
</P>
<P>
Most of the excavated tombs are one-room brick burial chambers,
according to the archaeologists. Funerary objects were found on
tables placed behind the burial beds, and several passageways
winding through the site were discovered.
</P>
<P>
Also unearthed were a dozen bronze coins of the Han Dynasty and
many burial objects, mostly earthenware.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists said that more items might have been found
if grave robbers had not plundered the site throughout history.
</P>
<P>
Xin Zhanshan, director of the Liaoning Institute of Relics and
Archaeology, said that never before have so many tombs from the
Han Dynasty been found in the western area of Liaoning. He said
he believes that more ancient tombs have yet to be found in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The site can provide useful information for research on burial
customs of the Han Dynasty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
