<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polo Originated in Tibet, Researcher Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scholar who specializes
in Tibetan research claims that the Western sport of polo
originated in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Polo, known as the "Game of Kings," was developed by ancient
Tibetans and later spread to Central Asia and Europe, Wang Yao
explains in his newly-published paper entitled "A New Study on
Polo."
</P>
<P>
The earliest Tibetan lexicon, dating back more than 1,000
years, provides corroborating evidence for polo's true beginnings,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
German American researcher B. Laufer, who also focuses on
Tibetan studies, said that the compilers of "The Century
Dictionary" and "Encyclopedia Britannica" regarded "polo" as an
ancient Tibetan word.
</P>
<P>
And "The New History of the Tang Dynasty" has recorded that
Tibetan dukes and princes gave treasures, including gold polo
mallets, to the emperor of the Tang Dynasty when asking to marry
into the royal family.
</P>
<P>
Ancient Tibetan people were renowned for their advanced polo
skills, according to the experts. The sport became particularly
popular in the capital city, Chang'an, of the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
He cited a Chinese history book which recorded interesting
games between Tang warriors and Tibetan envoys. After a streak of
losses, the emperor sent into the game a prince who showed off his
athletic prowess and led his team to victory.
</P>
<P>
Professor Han Guopan claimed that Tibetans liked playing polo
and people of the Han nationality studied the sport from Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
"Not only did the culture of the Han nationality have influence
over Tibetans, Tibet's civilization also enriched lives of the Han
people," Han said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
