<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Beer Back to Kenya After 15 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has begun exporting
beer to Kenya after a 15-year absence as the first consignment of
13,000 crates of Castle beer worth almost 24,000 U.S. Dollars
arrived here last week, the East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Our beer export to Kenya is due to demand. An importer in
Kenya with longstanding experience in the marketing of beer
products asked us for supplies," said Daniel Niemandt, managing
director of Tanzania Breweries Ltd. (TBL).
</P>
<P>
"We are very excited about the Kenya market as the TBL's main
shareholder. The South African Breweries and a Nairobi
businessman are in the final stages of setting up a brewery in
Thika," about 30 kilometers east of Nairobi, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The brewery is expected to begin operations in September next
year, and it will have the franchise to produce nearly all of our
brands," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He said the TBL has also received enquiries from Rwanda,
Uganda and Burundi, although the firm is yet to act on the
requests.
</P>
<P>
However, he denied that TBL's incursion into Kenya is part of
the trade war between TBL and the Kenya Breweries Ltd..
</P>
<P>
Kenya Breweries sells about 350,000 crates per month in
Tanzania through 30 local agents. Now it is also finalizing plans
for several joint venture beer plants in Tanzania. 
</P>
