<HEADLINE> East China Port on Route to Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Yantai Port in East China's
Shandong province is accelerating the pace of construction in a
major bid to build itself into a modernized coastal outlet.
</P>
<P>
The port authorities say that the second phase of the state's
key project will be completed within this year.
</P>
<P>
Situated in the northern part of the Shandong peninsula,
covering 864 square kilometers of water area, Yantai port is one
of the country's water transportation hubs and an important port
opened to the outside, playing an important role in the country's
comprehensive communications network.
</P>
<P>
The first phase project of Yantai port construction began to
operate in September 1990, with six deepwater berths
completed. Another six deepwater berths for multipal uses will be
completed during the second phase, with the yearly capacity of
handling 3.4 million tons of goods, which will be in operation
within this year.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the State Council, the third phase project of
Yantai port will begin this year. It will build seven deepwater
berths, with a yearly handling capacity of 3.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by the end of 1997, Yantai will build 34
berths, with 15 of them deepwater berths. The water front will be
5,200 meters long.
</P>
<P>
Passenger and goods transportation also got rapid development,
with a yearly capacity of handling 2.8 million passengers. The
port has opened over 20 container lines worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Yantai has direct communications with over one
hundred ports in 70 countries and regions, and it received over
800 foreign ships yearly. Yantai port handled over 14 million tons
of goods last year, including over 90,000 twenty equivalent units
(TEU) of containers.
</P>
<P>
Yantai port is divided into four areas for transportation of
passengers and goods, containers, individual goods and for other
uses.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2020, Yantai port will have 58 berths, over 43 of
which will be deepwater berths. It will handle 45 million tons of
goods yearly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
