<HEADLINE> Ugandan Researchers Cure Malaria with Herbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan researchers have
successfully cured 20 cases of malaria with herbs, "The New
Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Rukararwe Partnership Workshop for Rural Development, a
non-governmental organisation based in western Buyshenyi
district, reported it have founded herbs effective in fighting
malaria.
</P>
<P>
The report have been published in the British journal
"Tropical Doctor", volume 27, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The curing substance is a mixture extracted from some local
herbs living in water, but the paper did not name the herbs.
</P>
<P>
The herbs were confirmed to be harmless to the patients, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
"All cases that were treated, including those that did not
respond to conventional anti-malarials such as chloroquine,
sulfdoxine/sulphamethoxale and amodiaquine, responded to our
mixture," the report claimed.
</P>
<P>
The study were carried out by local traditional medicine
practitioners with a modern pharmacist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
