<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plateau Province Plans to Build Five Production Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai, a remote, landlocked
northwestern province on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, plans to
enhance local economic development by exploring its abundant
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), five major
bases producing hydroelectric power, chemical products,
non-ferrous metals, petrochemical products and grass-eating
animals are expected to be set up across the province.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai section of the upper reaches of the Yellow River,
the second largest in China, will be turned into a large
hydro-power generation base.
</P>
<P>
A number of hydroelectric power stations, including the
Lijiaxia station, which has a generating capacity of two million
kilowatts, and a 330 kw-transformation project, extending from the
Longyangxia Power Station to the city of Golmud, are scheduled to
be completed by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Being rich in salt resources, the province plans to develop a
series of chemical products such as potassium, sodium, magnesium,
lithium, strontium and boron.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the expansion projects in some
factories, Qinghai is expected to become the country's largest
producer of potash fertilizer and salt-based chemical products.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, by 2000, the province will become a major producer
and exporter of electrolysis aluminium, ferroalloy and
carborundum, with an annual production capacity of 400,000 tons of
aluminium, 15,000 tons of magnesium, 270,000 tons of ferroalloy,
10,000 tons of carborundum and 2,100 kg of gold.
</P>
<P>
The Qaidam Basin in the province has potential reserves of
petroleum and natural gas, with its proven oil and gas reserves
standing at 188 million tonz and 47.2 billion cu. m.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Qinghai is expected to have by 2000 an annual
production capacity of 20,000 tons of epoxy propane, 5,000 tons of
propylene glycol, 20,000 tons of polyether, 300,000 tons of
synthetic ammonia and 520,000 tons of carbamide.
</P>
<P>
The province also plans to develop its animal husbandry
industry by building more facilities able to withstand natural
disasters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
