<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Computers can be found in the
homes of nearly one-fifth of the urban families in Guangzhou,
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, a recent survey shows.
</P>
<P>
In the city, computers are now common in government offices,
scientific research institutions, media organizations, and even
kindergartens.
</P>
<P>
A wider variety of software is available, and computer services
have improved, according to the study. Computer prices dropped by
39 percent, and the price of a computer printer went down by 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that overall spending habits of people
in the city have also changed: In the first half of this year,
money spent on food only accounted for just over 50 percent of the
whole cost of living, much less than before.
</P>
<P>
Every household in the city has some sort of home appliance,
such as a refrigerator, washing machine or air-conditioner, and
more people have disposable income.  
</P>
