<HEADLINE> Nature Reserves Expanding in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that
China's nature reserves cover 720,000 sq. km., or 7.2 percent of
the nation's total landspace.
</P>
<P>
China's nature reserve coverage exceeds the international
average of six percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the National Environmental Protection Agency
(NEPA) show that the State Council has approved 799 state-level
nature reserves. In addition, 20-odd provinces have established
special committees in charge of local reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry, the Ministry of Agriculture, the
Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources, the National Bureau of
Oceanography, and NEPA drafted a blueprint for the development of
China's nature reserves now being implemented with the approval
from the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of the nation's nature reserves have also
drafted internal development plans.
</P>
<P>
China has established a large number of nature reserves in
recent years to protect its prairie, desert, wetlands and ocean
areas. The goal of the reserves is to protect geological
formations, relics, forests and endangered species of plants and
animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
