<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gurkhas Threaten to Sue British Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The retired British Gurkha
soldiers has threatened that if the British government does not
meet their demand for equal treatment, they will drag it to the
court, Nepali newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing some 800 ex-Gurkha army and their families Sunday,
President of the Gorkha Army Ex-Servicemen Organization (GAESO)
Padam Bahadur Gurung said that they will wait for a dialog between
the governments of Nepal and Britain, if that does not materialize
or fail to address their grievances, they will go to London
courts.
</P>
<P>
A team of Ex-Gurkha officers, politicians and human rights
workers visited London recently and met with British politicians
and human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
"We talked with lawyers there who have assured that our case is
strong. A barrister is coming here soon to prepare and gather
necessary documents," Gurung said.
</P>
<P>
The GAESO threatened late last year that it would file a case
in a British court against the British government to fight the
"discrimination" meted to the Gurkhas if the issue is not settled
on governmental level by April 1997.
</P>
<P>
The demands raised by the GAESO include pension to the 10,000
Gurkhas who were sent back to Nepal after the Second World War and
the war between Malaysia and Indonesia in 1968.
</P>
<P>
The organization argued that about 70 percent of these Gurkha
soldiers have died, but their families are left without the
pension.
</P>
<P>
The second demand is to provide pensions for the Gurkhas on par
with their British counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Many Gurkhas receive as little as 24 pounds a month while the
British get 475 pounds, they said.
</P>
<P>
The organization also demand the rights for the British Gurkhas
to live and work in Britain after retirement.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in 1947 between Britain, India and
Nepal, the British and Indian armies can recruit Nepalese, who are
called the Gurkha soldiers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
