<HEADLINE> Indian Army Chief Sees Scope for Indo-Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Indian Army Chief
General Shankar Roy Chowdhury said on Sunday that there were
opportunities for Indo-Bangladesh military cooperation and his
country would "certainly" welcome such move.
</P>
<P>
"Military cooperation to a certain extent is already there," he
said in an interview with local newspaper the Daily Star. "But
we'd like to develop this certainly," if it is desired by both
countries, said the General, who arrived here on August 5 at the
invitation of his Bangladesh counterpart Lt. General Mahbubur
Rahman.
</P>
<P>
The existing level of cooperation between the geo-close
neighbors only covers training of officers of one country in the
military academy of the another countries.
</P>
<P>
General Chowdhury said Bangladesh's buying military hardware
from India was also a possibility. But he denied that this issue
was discussed in his week-long visit, expected to end today.
</P>
<P>
Chowdhury, who fought the Pakistan forces in Bangladesh's
independent war in 1971, called his visit a "goodwill" one,
designed to "further develop good relations between the armies of
India and Bangladesh and also between the two states".
</P>
<P>
"I have come here with on a goodwill visit to let the people of
Bangladesh know about the intention of the Indian armed forces,"
said the Indian General, whose country surrounds Bangladesh on
three sides.
</P>
<P>
General Chowdhury said that the two armed forces could
cooperate on different development issues like containing cross
border insurgency, terrorism, smuggling and many other vices which
hindered the economic growth of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Bangladesh, the Indian General called on
President Shahabuddin Ahmed, visited his paternal village
Taki-Shahidpur in Jessore district and also went to Chittagong,
Rangamati, Kaptai, Chogla, Sundarbans, Comilla and Sylhet.
</P>
</TEXT>
