<HEADLINE> India to Further Relax Import Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- India's Commerce Ministry is
planning to shift around 300 items from the restricted and
negative list to the open general license (OGL) list in a bid to
further relax its control on imports, a government official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The move is a part of an overall exercise to ease quantitative
restrictions on imports. India is due to lift all restrictions
gradually in accordance with her obligations to the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
India would stick to her initial offer at the consultations to
be held under the WTO's dispute settlement body, scheduled for
next month in Geneva. Last month, several developed countries had
sought dispute settlement consultations with India on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Indian Union Commerce Minister of State B.B. Ramaiah has said
that India could not agree to phase out all import curbs in less
than six years. Some developed countries have asked India to ease
its import restrictions within 2-3 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
