<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Crested Ibis Population Exceeding 100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The number of China's crested ibis
has gone above 100, as against only seven in 1981, when the country
first found the very rare birds in inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Some of the birds flew south from Yangxian County in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, and members of an ibis protection center
have successfully bred 28 crested ibises during the reproduction
period this spring, 21 of which are healthy and doing fine and
four young birds are well taken care of in the center's clinic.
</P>
<P>
In the arid summer, more than 30 members of the protection
center watched ten crested ibises around the clock and helped two
pairs of mature ibises change nests, ensuring reproduction.
</P>
<P>
They also took back three abandoned ibis eggs for further
observation and breeding, producing two young birds.
</P>
<P>
With the help of local farmers, they found new water sources
and planted 1,200 kg of loaches for the precious birds to feed on.
</P>
<P>
Crested ibises are found only in China and Japan. China listed
the crested ibis as a protected species in 1983, and 37 ibises
were reported in the country in a 1993 study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
