<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Resume Dollar Trading in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Bankers Association of the
Philippines will allow foreign banks to resume trading in the
foreign exchange spot market today but with certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks could start trading -- both buy and sell -- again
under an agreement reached at the organization's meeting over the
weekend, today's local press reports quoted Deogracias Vistan,
president of the association, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The foreign banks were "requested" by the association to
voluntarily stop trading on the foreign exchange spot market, the
Philippine Dealing System, on July 28 to help stabilize the
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"The market is pretty much going on its own already. The
association is agreeing to this change after considering the
foreign banks' balance contribution in the foreign exchange, "
Vistan said.
</P>
<P>
Among the conditions tied to the approval for foreign banks to
resume trading on the spot market is that they coordinate closely
with the association, he said.
</P>
<P>
For requirements above 10 million U.S. dollars, foreign banks
should first access the forward contract window of the Central
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
