<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse to Delist 30 Unqualified Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) will delist some 30 listed companies which fail to meet
established criteria, said SET President Singh Tangtatswas on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Singh said that he will be the first SET president in Thailand
to remove unqualified public firms from the market.
</P>
<P>
The stock market has seen voluntary withdrawals of three firms
and some others will be delisted soon, he was quoted as saying by
local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Thai stock market is introducing new regulations to ensure
that listed companies fulfill their obligations to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules which have yet to be approved by the
Securities and Exchange Commission, only larger and more qualified
companies will be allowed to be registered on the market and those
executives or managers who cause losses to shareholders will not
be allowed to run new public firms. 
</P>
