<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Large State Enterprises Look to New Issuances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Issuance of new A shares will
help China's large State-owned enterprises with their stock
structure, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper reported that a recent general
meeting of Hong Hong-and-Shenzhen-listed Jilin Chemical Co Ltd
proposed to issue 300 million new A shares.
</P>
<P>
If approved by the government, the issuance will be the first
of its kind in China's securities market.
</P>
<P>
The company had issued 960 million H shares and 50 million A
shares with total stock capital of 3.4 billion yuan (409 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The China Securities Regulatory Commission has also confirmed
that among this year's 30 billion yuan worth of new shares issuing
quota, some will be used by large State-owned enterprises to issue
new A shares.
</P>
<P>
The increased A-share issuance will help listed State
enterprises to raise more funds while also improving the stock
structure of such companies.
</P>
<P>
An analysis in the newspaper "China Securities" said some
companies listed in both Hong Kong and domestic exchanges have a
"typical irrational stock structure," meaning that they generally
have big total capital stock but a small volume of A shares in
circulation.
</P>
<P>
This can easily lead to manipulation in the stock market if
investors try to control the composite index through buying and
selling shares in such companies.
</P>
<P>
The "China Securities" analysis said that the new A shares
issued by large State-owned enterprises will be characterized by
large volume and low price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
