<HEADLINE> Fujian Drafts Rules to Oversee Earthquake Relief Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A regulation aimed to help
prevent earthquakes and improve disaster-relief work in east
China's Fujian Province has been drafted by local legislator.
</P>
<P>
The move was prompted by minor or medium quakes repeatedly
metered in the province over recent years, according to a report
in today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Fujian is among the regions in the country most prone to
earthquakes because it is located in the earthquake belt that
entails the southeast coast and is close to Taiwan, which is in
the Pacific region that has the most dynamic seismic activity in
the world.
</P>
<P>
A recent quake on May 30 in Yong'an County, measured 5.2
degrees on the Richter scale, caused direct economic losses as
high as 73.5 million yuan (8.8 million US dollars), said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up an earthquake-relief system that
involves monitoring, forecasting, prevention, emergency and rescue
measures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, legislation has also been passed in the province
providing for rules and regulations to help disaster relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
