<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Accident Record Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China has reported a significant
decrease in the number of industrial accidents in the first five
months of this year, accordig to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
A document from the Ministry of Labour disclosed that there
were 5,737 industrial accidents and 6,117 deaths, down 12.8
percent and 8.6 percent respectively compared with the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The accidents included 296 major incidents in which 2,058
people died, down by 15.4 percent and 1.8 percent respectively
over last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has taken a series of measures over the past
few years to ensure safety in production.
</P>
<P>
According to a safety-promotion program mapped out by the
ministry at the end of 1995, both central and local governments
should invest more in safety measures when drawing up the annual
financial budget.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also issued some regulations to promote safety in
production, including the Regulation for Supervising Industrial
Safety in Mines, in a bid to remove the danger of industrial
accidents.
</P>
<P>
The document, which sum up the ministry's work in the first
half of this year, also said that average wage levels has
increased although the workforce had shrunk.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the average monthly salary was 2,904
yuan (349 US dollars) in the first half of this year adjusted for
inflation, representing 5.1 percent growth in real terms over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
And the total payment to the workforce reached 427.99 billion
yuan (51 million US dollars) by June, a rise of 9.9 percent over
the same period in 1966. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
