<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Car Sales Help Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese domestic car makers sold
226,900 of the 238,000 cars they produced in the first half of
this year, increases of 25 percent and 23 percent respectively
from last year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40 percent of vehicles, notes a report released by the
Ministry of Machine Building Industry (MMBI), were purchased by
individual buyers.
</P>
<P>
In the Asian Games Village Automobile Exchange, Beijing's
largest car dealer, the ratio of privately bought cars to total
sales, for the first six months, ranged from 61 percent to 98.4
percent - depending on models sold.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the number of the private car users, rather than
institutional buyers, will increase rapidly in the future," said
Zhang Xiaoyu, MMBI automotive department director, at a recent
press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Only through conspicuous change in consumption can China's
auto sector have promising prospects," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Insiders believe that the Highway Law passed by the National
People's Congress last month will boost auto sales next year -- by
replacing road tolls with fuel fees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970811.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mining Fees Enforced to Preserve Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The collection of levies from
mining units for the exploitation of mineral resources has been
going well this year, despite some problems, "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quotes Jiang Chengsong,
vice-minister of geology and mineral resources as saying that the
rate of the fee to be collected varies in proportion to the output
volume and value of the mining sector in any particular year.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the ministry has set the collection
quota from mining units at one billion yuan (120 million US
dollars) each year. Yet the ministry failed to fill the quota in
1995, the first year the system was put into practice. The total
money collected that year was far less than the quota set by the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The turning point came in 1996 when the one billion yuan (120
million US dollars) quota was fulfilled, ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
As the money collected by May this year has exceeded 240
million yuan (28.9 million US dollars), almost the same amount as
in the previous year, the ministry is confident of reaching this
year's quota.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
